ğŸ§   Replication controler 
Replication Controller ensures that a specified number of pod replicas are always running.
If any pod fails or gets deleted, it automatically creates a new one.

â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
ğŸ§   difference between ReplicaSet, Deployment, and StatefulSet and daemonSet in Kubernetes ğŸ‘‡

 1ï¸âƒ£ ReplicaSet (RS)                                                  # it is used in stateless application
Ensures a specific number of identical pods are always running.
âœ” Auto-restart
âœ” Auto-scale
âŒ No rolling updates
âŒ No version control
âŒ No stable network identity
ğŸ‘‰ Used inside Deployment automatically.
ğŸ‘‰ You rarely create ReplicaSet directly.

âœ… 2ï¸âƒ£ Deployment                                                         # it is used in stateless application
Manages ReplicaSets + provides rolling updates and rollbacks.
 in this we have extra features like rollback and rolling update 
  Deployment in Kubernetes is a higher-level resource that manages the deployment and lifecycle of your applicationâ€™s pods. 
  It allows you to define the desired state of your application, such as the number of replicas, 
  the version of the application, and how updates should be rolled out. Kubernetes then takes care of ensuring that the current state matches the desired state.

Deployment is used in real time for stateless applications like web apps and APIs that require rolling updates and scaling.

In real time, Deployment manages ReplicaSets to handle scaling, rolling updates, and rollbacks, while ReplicaSets ensure the required number of pods are always running.
Deployment
   â†“
ReplicaSet
   â†“
Pods
ReplicaSet handles pod count
Deployment handles rollout & rollback
âœ” Rolling updates
âœ” Rollbacks
âœ” Version control
âœ” Easy to scale
âŒ No unique identity
âŒ Not for database-type workloads
ğŸ‘‰ Best for stateless applications like:
Nginx
Node.js
Python
Java apps
APIs

âœ… 3ï¸âƒ£ StatefulSet
Used for stateful applications where each pod needs a fixed identity.
âœ” Stable pod name (pod-0, pod-1...)     # If a Pod crashes or is deleted, Kubernetes recreates it with the same name.
âœ” Stable network identity
âœ” Stable storage (PVC per pod)
âœ” Ordered startup & shutdown
âŒ Slower scaling
âŒ Not needed for stateless apps
ğŸ‘‰ Used for databases:
MySQL
MongoDB

StatefulSet is used in real time for databases and stateful workloads that need stable identity and persistent storage.
StatefulSet provides stable pod names and a dedicated PVC for each pod, ensuring data persistence and correct identity in stateful applications.
if the pod restart by any chance then the data is still safe. 
StatefulSet
   â†“
Pods (directly)
   â†“
PVCs (one per pod)
No ReplicaSet in between.

apiVersion: apps/v1                  # API group/version that supports StatefulSet
kind: StatefulSet                   # Declares this object as a StatefulSet (for stateful apps)
metadata:
  name: mysql                       # Name of the StatefulSet (pods: mysql-0, mysql-1, mysql-2)
spec:
  serviceName: mysql                # Headless Service name (required for stable DNS)
                                    # Enables mysql-0.mysql, mysql-1.mysql, etc.
  replicas: 3                       # Number of MySQL pods to run
  selector:                         # Defines which pods this StatefulSet manages
    matchLabels:
      app: mysql                    # Pods with this label belong to this StatefulSet
  template:                         # Pod template (used to create each pod)
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: mysql                  # Pod label (must match selector above)
    spec:
      terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 30
                                    # Time (seconds) given to MySQL to shut down gracefully
                                    # Prevents data corruption
      containers:
      - name: mysql                 # Container name inside the pod
        image: mysql:8.0            # Docker image pulled from Docker Hub
                                    # mysql = repository, 8.0 = version tag
        ports:
        - containerPort: 3306       # MySQL default port inside the container
          name: mysql               # Named port (used by Service)
        env:                        # Environment variables passed to MySQL
        - name: MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD # Sets root password (required to start MySQL)
          value: rootpassword       # Plain text password (use Secret in production)
        - name: MYSQL_DATABASE      # Database created automatically at startup
          value: appdb
        - name: MYSQL_USER          # Non-root user created automatically
          value: appuser
        - name: MYSQL_PASSWORD      # Password for the non-root user
          value: apppassword
        volumeMounts:
        - name: mysql-data          # Volume name (must match PVC template below)
          mountPath: /var/lib/mysql # Directory where MySQL stores its data files
  volumeClaimTemplates:             # Template for PersistentVolumeClaims
                                    # Kubernetes creates ONE PVC per pod
  - metadata:
      name: mysql-data              # Base PVC name
                                    # Actual PVCs:
                                    # mysql-data-mysql-0
                                    # mysql-data-mysql-1
                                    # mysql-data-mysql-2
    spec:
      accessModes:
      - ReadWriteOnce               # Volume can be mounted by only ONE pod
                                    # Required for databases
      storageClassName: my-storage-class
                                    # Storage provisioner used
                                    # Example: gp3, standard, local-path
      resources:
        requests:
          storage: 10Gi             # Disk size allocated PER pod
                                    # Total storage = 3 Ã— 10Gi

Resource	               apiVersion
Pod      	                  v1	 
